Memo: Gary Lund Classic. Well, this race had everything... Chain derailed, stopped and fixed and rode backup to the pack. Luckly, the pack was going very slow, 25 kph, so I caught up to the pack easily. Then I got stuck behind a  crash. Stopped completely and put my foot down. Rode hard to catch backup. Mainly drafing of others as they came by. Then got caught behind another crash on a single lane bridge. This all happen before the turn around. On the way back lost contact with the lead pack going up a steep climb. Took me a while to recover. When I did I rode very well with a four other cyclists. Then about 12 Km from the finish, I flated. Finished the race with a flat tyre. Oh well. The weather was wonderful and the B&B was amazing! Most go back to that one next year. I think I would like to finish my career placing top 7 at this race.

Memo: The big day. The Tour de Delta road race. I was not going to miss this one. Fixed up the bike the day before and was ready to roll. I am writing this on Monday and thinking back it was the perfect race. The race started at 8:00 am under cloudy skies, which was good to keep the tempature down.  Did two and a half loops in North Delta. Traffic was stopped for us and we had the complete road. Helicopter over head filming as we crossed from North Delta to South Delta along Highway 10. I was to learn later that the race was already over as the main pack turned from 114th to Highway 10. The pace was amazing fast as the pack rode single file from north to south Delta. It was a strong northly wind and drafting was essential. Into to Tswwassen to start the first of 11 loops. I felt good and was willing to work harder. Unfortunately, was was not drinking or eating well and the distance caught upto me on the 7 time up the hill. The pace was not hard, but was merely completely drained. I picked up the food on the very last possible feeding lap but it was too late. I wish I had start drinking Coke or Gatoraid two or three later earler. I am still happy with my perforance and truely feel under performed on that day.

Memo:
The final day, Fossil to Heppner - 136 KM. This course had four climbs. The first is a climb of 1200 feet over eight miles followed by a downhill over 2000 feet in 12 miles. The main pack was still together at this point. A flat run of 12 miles to a 13 mile climb of 2800 feet. This broke up the main group, which was about 30 people, in half. I was with the lead pack at this point, the flat run to the third climb, the second feed zone, was fast and really weakened me. As soon as we hit the hill, pop! off the back I went. I rode the remainer by myself, well with the help of a Cat 1/2 rider. I managed to finished ahead of the second chase group, which was dropped on the second climb.
Start the day 53 overall, by the end of the day, jumped up to 38 overall!

Memo: Drove down to Heppner for the Columbia Plateau stage race...

First stage - Heppner to Ione - 88 Km. Did know what to expect. Went to the front on the first 12 mile hill and attacked for a minute or two. Good timing as it placed me near the front for the long decent. The race highlight was the horses that entered the course! About half way into the race, two horse ran into the road and ran along the side of the road. Once the horses entered the road, broke the pack in two. With the lead pack riding faster to stay clear and the back half riding slower to avoid the horses. They were big powerful horses. This continued for about 2 miles. They began to tire, and one horse bumped they other, causing a horse to run sail over a barred wire fence knocking out a fence post. General, a large group 80+ finished together - 2:22:24.

T.T. in the moring, 3.2 km - finished 50th with a time of 6:49. Had lunch and then rode a 100 km race. I attached at the 25 km mark. I was on my own for 5 KM until I was joined with two others. We rode so hard that we caught the Cat 1/2, which had start early by looping out on some other course and then joining ours. 

We worked hard, but only gaining a minute thirty on the chase pack. We got caught on false flat, but could not stay with them. Rode the remaining 50 km by myself. I was hurting! Only lost 14 minutes to the leaders.

Record setting ride. Drove Leanda's car out to Roberts bank, warmed-up and then attempted to break Route #1 best time. Started at 10:30 and rode towards White Rock. Confortabily rode at 40 KM/H along Delta Port rode and HW 10 using 53 x 19. Good spin on the way out. I was breathing hard, but conserving leg strength by riding at a high rpm. At the 7.5 KM mark, I was at 11:55 and by the time I reached White Rock, I was 1 minute and 40 second ahead of a 100 minute time (100 minutes = 1:40:00). Which was good news as I needed to better 1:39:19. As I turned around, the wind was pretty neutral until Scott rode. With each kilometer closer to Roberts back - and the ocean - the winds strenght increased. On the way back along HW 10 between the police station and Ladner, I had to be very streamlined in order to cheat the wind and maintain an average to 37+ KM/H. The core strength training really payed of as I maintained an areo position and finished with a time of 1:38:31. 

PS - The Odometer was set on Auto start, stop. My time would be about 10 to 15 secoinds less if I used manual setting. Still, best time overall. 1 down, 6 to go...
